        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We estimate the expected CO and HCO^+ line depths based on the known flux densities of the five lensed image components of PMN J0134-0931 (the sixth component has negligible flux density at high frequencies). The 15 GHz VLBA image of the source shows that the five components have flux densities of 143 mJy, 38 mJy, 28 mJy, 26 mJy and 12 mJy at 15 GHz (Winn et al. 2003). All five components have a spectral index of -0.69 from 1.7 GHz to 43 GHz (Winn et al. 2002, 2003). This yields flux densities of 2.7-32.2 mJy for the five components at 130 GHz, the frequency of the redshifted CO(2-1) line, and 3.2-38.3 mJy at 101 GHz, the frequency of the redshifted HCO^+(2-1) line. Given the very high OH column density (&gt; 10^{15} per cm^2, from the observed conjugate behaviour; Kanekar et al. 2005), the H_2 column density should be very high as well (&gt;~ 10^{22} per cm^2), implying that the CO and HCO^+ lines should be optically thick. We hence aim to detect optically-thick CO and HCO^+ absorption against the weakest of the lensed images, implying a line depth of ~2.7 mJy at 130 GHz and 3.2 mJy at 101 GHz. 

We note that it might appear most efficient to use either CO or HCO^+ absorption for the detection of mm-wave molecular absorption. However, the relative strengths of the CO and HCO^+ absorption depend on the type of gas, with CO absorption being stronger in dense gas and HCO^+ absorption stronger in diffuse gas. It is hence important to search for both CO and HCO^+ absorption. Of course, the detection of both transitions will immediately also yield interesting science results for the system.

Based on the results from B0218+357 and B1830-210, the mm-wave absorption is likely to be significantly narrower than the OH or HI-21cm absorption; we hence assume velocity FWHM of ~ 10 km/s for the absorption lines, similar to values in the two known gravitational lenses. Our aim is to detect the absorption at 5 sigma significance, implying required RMS noise values of ~ 0.54 mJy per 10 km/s channel at the redshifted CO(2-1) line frequency (130.6 GHz) and of ~ 0.64 mJy per 10 km/s channel at the redshifted HCO^+(2-1) line frequency (101.1 GHz). We have used the ALMA sensitivity calculator to find that the above sensitivity requirement can be achieved (with 34 antennas in Cycle 2) in ~ 1.26 hours of on-source time in Band-4 for the CO(2-1) line and ~ 58 minutes of on-source time in Band-3 for the HCO^+(2-1) line. The total times, including calibration and overheads, are 2.8 hours and 2.1 hours, respectively. Our total time request is then 4.9 hours, 2.1 hours in Band-3 and 2.8 hours in Band-4.

The 5 lensed image components of J0134-0931 are very compact, arranged in a circle of diameter ~ 0.7''. We aim for a synthesized beam of size ~ 0.2", sufficient to resolve out the lens components.
We request that the correlator be set up in FDM mode. The Band-4 observations will use two 1.875 GHz spectral windows with 3840 channels (i.e. a velocity resolution of ~ 2 km/s at 130.6 GHz), covering the CO(2-1) line, and a second transition, the CN(2-1) line, along with two spectral windows used in low-resolution mode (centred at 140.3 and 142.3 GHz) to obtain a continuum image. The Band-3 observations will also use two 1.875 GHz spectral windows with 3840 channels, covering the HCO^+(2-1) line and both the HNC(2-1) and H2O 183 GHz lines (with ~ 2.8 km/s velocity resolution), along with 2 low-resolution continuum windows (centred at 89.3 and 91.2 GHz). The HNC and H2O lines are 'complimentary' and we do not base the sensitivity estimate on these. If detected, they will provide additional scientific results to this proposal.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We will have the targetted absorption lines in one sideband and have set up the other sideband for continuum observations. The linewidth is largely unknown, but from OH observations we estimate that it will not be smaller than 10 km/s.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The angular resolution is dictated by the need to resolve the lensed image components of PMN0134-0931. A resolution of 0.2" is sufficient to discriminate between all the lens components and determine against which the absorption is occuring. The imaging part does not require high dynamic range but will only be used to identify the absorption components with the corresponding molecular absorption components.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
